<figureCitation box="[495,577,1596,1622]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–34" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1043,1067]" captionTargetBox="[162,1423,189,1009]" captionTargetId="figure-21@8.[151,1436,181,1019]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 29–34. Hind legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 29. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 30. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 31. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 32. P. plauta sp. nov.; 33. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 34. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816733/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="520">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
) and the anterior margin of the middle tibia (
<figureCitation box="[1091,1173,1596,1622]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–28" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[163,1426,1001,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-396@7.[152,1436,993,1881]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 23–28. Middle legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 23. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 24. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 25. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 26. P. plauta sp. nov.; 27. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 28. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816731" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816731/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="520">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
) without a tuft of stout bristles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="522" pageId="13" pageNumber="520" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1416,2018]" lastBlockId="14.[151,1437,151,681]" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="521" pageId="13" pageNumber="520">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,524,1668,1694]" pageId="13" pageNumber="520">Description. Apterous male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[538,606,1668,1695]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[253,1330,191,1911]" captionTargetId="figure-18@3.[241,1345,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Habitus of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 1. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 2. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 3. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 4. P. plauta sp. nov.; 5. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 6. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816717" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816717/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="520">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Color: ground color dark-brown, head black, clypeus brown, rostum yellowish-brown with black apex, buccula dark-brown; antennal segment I yellowish-brown, apical part infuscated, segments II–IV brown; pronotum yellowish-brown, with dense black spots on posterior part, lateral part of metanotum black; legs (
<figureCitation box="[369,464,1776,1802]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–22" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1173,1197]" captionTargetBox="[159,1414,193,1138]" captionTargetId="figure-21@6.[151,1436,181,1149]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 17–22. Fore legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 17. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 18. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 19. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 20. P. plauta sp. nov.; 21. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 22. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816727" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816727/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="520">Figs. 21</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[477,507,1776,1802]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–28" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[163,1426,1001,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-396@7.[152,1436,993,1881]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 23–28. Middle legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 23. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 24. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 25. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 26. P. plauta sp. nov.; 27. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 28. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816731" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816731/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="520">27</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[520,549,1776,1802]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–34" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1043,1067]" captionTargetBox="[162,1423,189,1009]" captionTargetId="figure-21@8.[151,1436,181,1019]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 29–34. Hind legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 29. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 30. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 31. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 32. P. plauta sp. nov.; 33. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 34. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816733/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="520">33</figureCitation>
) mainly yellowish-brown, femora yellowish, apical part of femora infuscated, tibiae and tarsi yellowish-brown, grasping combs brown; mediotergites black, connexiva black with dull-orange margin, lateral part of mediotergite I, medial parts of mediotergites II, III, VI, VII and lateral margins of connexival segments I–V with prominent silvery pubescence; abdominal segment VIII (
<figureCitation box="[1007,1100,1884,1910]" captionStart="FIGURES 35–40" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1771,1795]" captionTargetBox="[174,1415,226,1669]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[151,1436,211,1681]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 35–40. Abdominal segment VIII of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 35. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 36. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 37. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 38. P. plauta sp. nov.; 39. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 40. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816737" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816737/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="520">Figs. 39</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1113,1143,1884,1911]" captionStart="FIGURES 47–52" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1860,1884]" captionTargetBox="[173,1410,201,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-18@11.[151,1436,181,1808]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 47–52. Abdominal segment VIII of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 47. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 48. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 49. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 50. P. plauta sp. nov.; 51. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 52. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816743" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816743/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="520">51</figureCitation>
), pygophore (
<figureCitation box="[1299,1380,1884,1910]" captionStart="FIGURES 59–64" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1165,1189]" captionTargetBox="[234,1369,196,1128]" captionTargetId="figure-18@13.[205,1381,181,1141]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 59–64. Pygophore of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 59. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 60. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 61. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 62. P. plauta sp. nov.; 63. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 64. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816747" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816747/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="520">Fig. 63</figureCitation>
) and proctiger pale-yellowish, each of them weakly infuscated apically. Structural characteristics: body small-sized, relatively stout, oval-like, bearing short, grayish setae, area around eyes and antennal segment I covered by relatively few, longer, grayish setae, outer margin of eyes covered by relatively dense, short, silver pubescence. Head short and wide, relatively perpendicular to thorax, without inflection; buccula not produced posteriorly; eyes bare except for the presence of two ocular setae. Pronotum relatively broad, bearing dense, dark punctures on the posterior portion of lobe, anterior and hind pronotal margins nearly straight; metanotum completely hidden beneath pronotal lobe except laterally. Fore tibia (
<figureCitation box="[432,513,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–22" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1173,1197]" captionTargetBox="[159,1414,193,1138]" captionTargetId="figure-21@6.[151,1436,181,1149]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 17–22. Fore legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 17. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 18. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 19. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 20. P. plauta sp. nov.; 21. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 22. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816727" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816727/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="521">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
) with widened apex, covered with dense, short, brown setae, medial part of venter on fore tibia with slight process, grasping comb relatively thin; middle femur (
<figureCitation box="[1041,1124,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–28" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[163,1426,1001,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-396@7.[152,1436,993,1881]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 23–28. Middle legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 23. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 24. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 25. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 26. P. plauta sp. nov.; 27. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 28. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816731" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816731/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="521">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
) covered with dense, short, grayish setae, middle tibia covered with dense, short, brown setae and few, long, suberect, brown hairs; hind tibia (
<figureCitation box="[159,241,367,393]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–34" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1043,1067]" captionTargetBox="[162,1423,189,1009]" captionTargetId="figure-21@8.[151,1436,181,1019]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 29–34. Hind legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 29. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 30. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 31. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 32. P. plauta sp. nov.; 33. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 34. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816733/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="521">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
) slightly curved, covered with dense, suberect, brown and bristle-like setae, apical part of lateral margin of hind tarsal segment I with a tuft of suberect, long, black bristles, apical part of hind tarsal segment I with a distinct process (
<figureCitation box="[251,336,439,465]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–34" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1043,1067]" captionTargetBox="[162,1423,189,1009]" captionTargetId="figure-21@8.[151,1436,181,1019]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 29–34. Hind legs of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 29. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 30. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 31. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 32. P. plauta sp. nov.; 33. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 34. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816733/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="521">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
), ventral arolium bristle-like. Abdomen almost flat, connexiva slightly raised, with suberect, few, long and brown setae; abdominal venter flat. Genital segments: small, segment VIII (
<figureCitation box="[1099,1192,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 35–40" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1771,1795]" captionTargetBox="[174,1415,226,1669]" captionTargetId="figure-18@9.[151,1436,211,1681]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 35–40. Abdominal segment VIII of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 35. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 36. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 37. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 38. P. plauta sp. nov.; 39. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 40. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816737" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816737/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="521">Figs. 39</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1203,1233,474,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 41–46" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1813,1837]" captionTargetBox="[151,1427,216,1720]" captionTargetId="figure-21@10.[151,1436,211,1738]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 41–46. Abdominal segment VIII of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 41. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 42. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 43. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 44. P. plauta sp. nov.; 45. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 46. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816739" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816739/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="521">45</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1245,1275,474,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 47–52" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1860,1884]" captionTargetBox="[173,1410,201,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-18@11.[151,1436,181,1808]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 47–52. Abdominal segment VIII of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 47. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 48. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 49. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 50. P. plauta sp. nov.; 51. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 52. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816743" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816743/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="521">51</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1287,1316,474,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 53–58" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1862,1886]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,182,1778]" captionTargetId="figure-21@12.[151,1436,181,1795]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 53–58. Abdominal segment VIII of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 53. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 54. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 55. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 56. P. plauta sp. nov.; 57. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 58. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816745" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816745/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="521">57</figureCitation>
) relatively stout, about 2.0 times as long as wide, hind margin with a very few, long, brown, suberect setae, ventrally with subtriangular depression, hind margin of the depression with a tuft of short, bristle-like setae; lateral margin of depression with a pair of bristle-like setae, longitudinal midline of the depression bearing a row of short setae apically; hind margin of pygophore (
<figureCitation box="[457,537,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURES 59–64" captionStartId="13.[151,264,1165,1189]" captionTargetBox="[234,1369,196,1128]" captionTargetId="figure-18@13.[205,1381,181,1141]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 59–64. Pygophore of Pseudovelia spp. (males). 59. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 60. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 61. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 62. P. plauta sp. nov.; 63. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 64. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816747" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816747/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="521">Fig. 63</figureCitation>
) with very short, erect, yellowish setae; proctiger small, hind margin with dense, short, yellowish setae; parameres symmetrical, small, with widened apex.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816749" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6816749" box="[151,824,1950,1974]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816749/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="521" startId="14.[151,250,1950,1974]" targetBox="[158,1427,715,1916]" targetPageId="14">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,824,1950,1974]" box="[151,824,1950,1974]" pageId="14" pageNumber="521">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,288,1950,1974]" pageId="14" pageNumber="521">FIGURE 65.</emphasis>
Geographical distribution of species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hoberlandt" authorityYear="1950" box="[694,818,1950,1974]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Pseudovelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="521" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[694,818,1950,1974]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="521">Pseudovelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,150,753]" pageId="15" pageNumber="522">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,398,150,176]" pageId="15" pageNumber="522">Apterous female</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[416,500,150,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–12" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[271,1323,194,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-21@4.[254,1333,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. Habitus of Pseudovelia spp. (apterous females). 7. P. buccula Andersen, 1983; 8. P. takarai Miyamoto, 1964; 9. P. curvisetae sp. nov.; 10. P. plauta sp. nov.; 11. P. shaanxiensis sp. nov.; 12. P. zhengi sp. nov. Scale 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816721" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816721/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="522">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Color: similar to male. Structural characteristics: body small-sized; structure of head including antenna as in male; hind margin of pronotum straight; fore tibia without grasping comb, hind tibia and tarsus not modified, venter of hind tarsal segment I lacking black, long bristles; abdomen pleurally and ventrally without special modifications, connexiva slightly raised, converging posteriorly and touching caudally; end of abdomen raised in lateral view, gonocoxa I elongate, proctiger brown, with dense, short hairs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,150,753]" box="[199,871,330,356]" pageId="15" pageNumber="522">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,752,330,356]" pageId="15" pageNumber="522">Macropterous female and macropterous male:</emphasis>
unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,150,753]" pageId="15" pageNumber="522">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,567,366,392]" pageId="15" pageNumber="522">Measurements. Apterous male.</emphasis>
Body length: 2.00, head width: 0.51, head length: 0.30, head width about 1.70 times head length; antenna about 0.60 times as long as body, length of antennal segments I–IV: 0.33, 0.24, 0.25, 0.38; pronotum width: 0.70, pronotum length: 0.35, about 2.00 times as wide as long; length of grasping comb 0.25, about 0.50 times tibial length; length of leg segments (femur, tibia and tarsus): fore leg: 0.50, 0.56, 0.30, middle leg: 0.79, 0.83, 0.54 (0.18+0.36), hind leg: 0.73, 1.00, 0.69 (0.19+0.50). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[957,1160,510,536]" pageId="15" pageNumber="522">Apterous female.</emphasis>
Body length: 2.31–2.33, head width: 0.53–0.55, head length: 0.30–0.31, head width about 1.77 times head length; antenna about 0.52 times as long as body, length of antennal segments I–IV: 0.36, 0.25, 0.25, 0.36; pronotum width: 0.72–0.75, pronotum length: 0.33–0.34, about 2.21 times as wide as long; length of leg segments (femur, tibia and tarsus): fore leg: 0.56, 0.51, 0.30, middle leg: 0.74, 0.73, 0.44 (0.13+0.31), hind leg: 0.81, 0.93, 0.48 (0.15+0.33).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1364,690,717]" pageId="15" pageNumber="522" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,150,753]" box="[199,1364,690,717]" pageId="15" pageNumber="522">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,690,716]" pageId="15" pageNumber="522">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the name of the 
<typeStatus box="[927,975,691,717]" pageId="15" pageNumber="522">type</typeStatus>
locality, 
<collectingRegion box="[1078,1278,690,716]" country="China" name="Shaanxi" pageId="15" pageNumber="522">Shaanxi Province</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1289,1360,690,716]" name="China" pageId="15" pageNumber="522">China</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,656,726,753]" pageId="15" pageNumber="522" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,150,753]" box="[199,656,726,753]" pageId="15" pageNumber="522">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,726,752]" pageId="15" pageNumber="522">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,426,726,752]" name="China" pageId="15" pageNumber="522">China</collectingCountry>
(Shannxi) (
<figureCitation box="[559,643,726,753]" captionStart="FIGURE 65" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1950,1974]" captionTargetBox="[158,1427,715,1916]" captionTargetId="figure-283@14.[151,1436,705,1926]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 65. Geographical distribution of species of Pseudovelia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6816749" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6816749/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="522">Fig. 65</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
